{
  "texts": [
    "Increasing crop diversity at the individual farmer level is both a strategy of bet-hedging (spreading the risk of potential epidemics across multiple crops) and of effective agro-ecological crop protection that reduces pest spread in the advent of an outbreak.",
    "The application of the same idea at the landscape scale (Picard et al. 2019), in addition to its use as a mean for managing pest-resistant varieties (Rimbaud et al. 2021), can extend benefits beyond a single farm, but requires coordination of stakeholders toward a common goal (Kneeshaw et al. 2021).",
    "Other coordination issues arise in the definition of a surveillance strategy and the implementation of a surveillance network.",
    "For this reason, and for reasons of efficiency (optimal allocation of resources, large-scale view of spatio-temporal pest detection patterns), state-level administration of pest surveillance is often required.",
    "The funding of surveillance is also a key challenge, which may need state intervention as well as the involvement of non-agricultural actors providing human and economic resources, especially when a pest is not yet present."
  ]
}